Login mechanics — PAM and shell startup files.

Two final pieces round out this module: how the system authenticates you in the first place, and what runs once it lets you in.

Start with PAM, which stands for Pluggable Authentication Modules. Here's the key insight: when you log in, or run su, or run sudo, those programs don't actually check your credentials themselves. They hand the job to PAM. And that indirection is powerful, because it turns authentication into a matter of configuration rather than code. Want to add two-factor authentication? Drop in a PAM module. Want to authenticate against LDAP or Active Directory? A PAM module. Want to enforce password complexity rules? Again, a module. The configuration lives in the etc-pam-dot-d directory, with one file per service, so there's a file for sshd, one for sudo, one for login, and so on.

Each of those files is organized around four management groups. The auth group verifies identity; it's the "prove you are who you say you are" step. The account group checks account status; it asks "is this account actually allowed to log in right now?", catching things like expired or locked accounts. The password group governs password changes, enforcing complexity and history rules. And the session group handles setup and teardown around a login, things like mounting your home directory, logging the login, and setting resource limits. You'll rarely write PAM rules from scratch, but you might read etc-pam-dot-d-slash-sshd to understand why a login is being denied. And one serious warning: a PAM misconfiguration can lock you out of the machine entirely, so always keep a root session open while you edit these files.

The second piece is shell startup files, which set up your environment the moment you're in. Which files run depends on the type of shell. A login shell, the kind you get from a text console, from SSH, or from su dash alice, reads etc-profile and then your bash-profile. An interactive non-login shell, like opening a new terminal window or just running bash, reads etc-bash-dot-bashrc and then your bashrc.

By convention, your bashrc holds your aliases, your shell functions, and your prompt customization, while your bash-profile holds your environment variable exports and PATH changes. And a very common trick is to have bash-profile simply source your bashrc, so the same settings apply whether the shell is a login shell or not. These are exactly the dotfiles we hinted at back in module three; now you know what they're for. After editing one, run source, tilde-slash-bashrc, to apply it immediately. And with that, you've got the full picture: who you are, where that's stored, how you prove it, and how the system sets you up once you're in.
